                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d423">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 841.51/41</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Great Britain</hi> (<persName
                        corresp="#p_PWH1" type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Page</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">London</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1917-03-09T15:00:00+00:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">March 9, 1917, 3 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                        <lb/> [<hi rend="italic">Received 5.30 p.m.</hi>]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>5817. My 5794, March 5, 1 p.m. The Governor of the Bank of England called on me
                    yesterday and confirmed every important statement made in my foregoing telegram.
                    He enlarged on the difficulty of shipping gold because of submarine danger and
                    is embarrassed to know how to pay for supplies from United States already
                    ordered. He asked me if it would now be possible for reserve banks in view of
                    submarine danger to take short time credits. He outlined a plan for the reserve
                    banks to rediscount ninety-day bills guaranteed by the Bank of England and asked
                    me to inquire if this could be done. Please instruct me what answer to give.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_PWH1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Page</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
